#let images = (
  "20.1": (
    caption: [Juvenile and adult forms of English ivy (*Hedera helix*). The juvenile form exhibits lobed palmate leaves arranged alternately, a climbing growth habit, and no flowers. In contrast, the adult form displays entire ovate leaves arranged in spirals, an upright growth habit, and the ability to produce flowers that develop into fruits. This phase change demonstrates developmental transitions in perennial plants.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.2": (
    caption: [Regulation of phase change in Arabidopsis by microRNAs. During the earliest stages of development, miR156 levels are very high and miR172 levels are very low, promoting the juvenile vegetative phase. Juvenile leaves are small and round with trichomes only on the adaxial side. As the plant ages, miR156 levels decline and miR172 levels increase, promoting the transition to adult vegetative phase with larger, more elongated leaves. Further increases in miR172 eventually promote reproductive phase transition. This demonstrates how temporal regulation of microRNAs controls developmental transitions.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.3": (
    caption: [Model for the endogenous circadian oscillator in plants. The circular diagram represents a 24-hour cycle, marked at 6-hour intervals (0h, 6h, 12h, and 18h), with daylight from 0h to 12h. The model shows interlocking feedback loops involving morning genes (LHY/CCA1), evening genes (TOC1/PRR family), and intermediate genes that create oscillating gene expression patterns. These feedback loops generate self-sustaining rhythms that regulate daily physiological processes.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.4": (
    caption: [Some characteristics of circadian rhythms. (A) A typical circadian rhythm showing the period (time between comparable points), phase points (recognizable positions in the cycle), and amplitude (distance between peak and trough). (B) Suspension of a circadian rhythm in continuous bright light and its release following transfer to darkness. (C) A circadian rhythm entrained to a 24-hour light-dark cycle and its reversion to free-running period (e.g., 26 hours) in continuous darkness. (D) Phase-shifting response to a light pulse given shortly after transfer to darkness, showing rhythm rephasing without period change.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.5": (
    caption: [Correlation between seasons and day length according to latitude. (A) Effect of latitude on day length at different times of the year in the northern hemisphere, with day length measured on day 20 of each month. At the equator, day length remains constant at 12 hours throughout the year. As latitude increases toward the poles, seasonal variation in day length increases dramatically, with longer days in summer and shorter days in winter. (B) Global map showing longitudes and latitudes to provide geographic context for photoperiodic responses.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.6": (
    caption: ['Maryland Mammoth' mutant of tobacco compared with wild-type tobacco. The mutant (right) is significantly larger than the wild type (left), despite both being grown during summer in the greenhouse. Maryland Mammoth is a short-day plant that fails to flower under the long summer days, allowing continuous vegetative growth, while wild-type tobacco flowers and stops growing. This historic mutant led to the discovery of photoperiodism in plants.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.7": (
    caption: [Photoperiodic response in long-day plants (LDPs) and short-day plants (SDPs). The graph shows flowering responses across different photoperiods. SDPs flower when the photoperiod is shorter than a critical duration, while LDPs flower when the photoperiod exceeds a critical duration. The critical duration varies among species. In this example, both SDPs and LDPs would flower in photoperiods between 12 and 14 hours long, representing an overlap zone.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.8": (
    caption: [Photoperiodic regulation of flowering. (A) Effects on SDPs and LDPs showing that the critical factor is the length of the dark period, not the light period. (B) Effects of the duration of the dark period on flowering, demonstrating that interrupting the dark period with a brief light exposure (night break) promotes flowering in LDPs but inhibits flowering in SDPs. This clearly shows that plants measure the length of the continuous dark period rather than the light period.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.9": (
    caption: [The time at which a night break is given determines the flowering response. When given during a long dark period, a night break promotes flowering in LDPs and inhibits flowering in SDPs. In both cases, the greatest effect on flowering occurs when the night break is given near the middle of the 16-hour dark period. This demonstrates that the effectiveness of night breaks varies rhythmically, suggesting involvement of the circadian clock in photoperiodic time measurement.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.10": (
    caption: [Rhythmic flowering in response to night breaks in soybean. In this experiment, the short-day plant soybean (*Glycine max*) received cycles of an 8-hour light period followed by a 64-hour dark period. A 4-hour night break was given at various times during the long inductive dark period. The flowering response, plotted as percentage of flowering, shows a clear circadian rhythm with peaks approximately 24 hours apart, demonstrating that sensitivity to night breaks oscillates with a circadian rhythm.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.11": (
    caption: [Molecular basis of the external coincidence model in Arabidopsis and rice. (A and B) In Arabidopsis under short days, there is little overlap between CO mRNA expression and daylight, so CO protein does not accumulate sufficiently to promote FT expression. Under long days, CO mRNA expression overlaps with daylight, allowing CO protein accumulation and FT activation. (C and D) Rice shows a similar mechanism but with opposite photoperiodic response, as rice Hd1 (CO ortholog) promotes flowering under short days and represses it under long days. This demonstrates how the external coincidence model explains photoperiodic flowering control.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.12": (
    caption: [Phytochrome control of flowering by red (R) and far-red (FR) light. A flash of red light during the dark period induces flowering in an LDP, and the effect is reversed by a subsequent flash of far-red light. This response indicates the involvement of phytochrome in photoperiodic responses. Conversely, in SDPs, a flash of red light prevents flowering, and far-red light reverses this inhibition. This demonstrates the photoreversible nature of phytochrome's role in flowering control.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.13": (
    caption: [Action spectra for the control of flowering by night breaks implicate phytochrome. Flowering in SDPs is inhibited by a short light treatment (night break) given during an otherwise inductive period. In the SDP *Xanthium strumarium*, red-light night breaks of 620 to 640 nm are most effective. Reversal of the red-light effect by far-red light (710-730 nm) confirms phytochrome involvement. The action spectrum matches the absorption spectrum of phytochrome, providing strong evidence for its role in photoperiodic responses.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.14": (
    caption: [Effect of far-red light on floral induction in Arabidopsis. At indicated times during a continuous 72-hour daylight period, 4 hours of far-red light were added. The data show a circadian rhythm of sensitivity to far-red light promotion of flowering, with peaks occurring approximately every 24 hours. This demonstrates that the plant's response to light quality varies rhythmically throughout the day, supporting the role of the circadian clock in photoperiodic responses.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.15": (
    caption: [Two grafting experiments demonstrating the translocation of a leaf-generated floral stimulus. (A) Grafting an induced leaf from a plant grown under short days onto a noninduced shoot causes the axillary shoots to produce flowers, demonstrating that a mobile signal moves from induced leaves to the shoot apex. (B) A noninduced scion grafted onto a vernalized rootstock flowers even though it was not vernalized, showing that the floral stimulus can move across graft unions. These experiments provided early evidence for a transmissible flowering signal, later identified as FLOWERING LOCUS T (FT) protein.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.16": (
    caption: [Multiple factors regulate flowering in Arabidopsis. The diagram shows the integration of environmental and developmental signals at the shoot apical meristem. FT protein (red arrows) is synthesized in leaf companion cells in response to photoperiod and CO protein, then transported through the phloem to the shoot apex. At the meristem, FT interacts with FD transcription factor to activate floral meristem identity genes like SOC1, LFY, and AP1. The leaf vein micrograph (bottom) shows FT-GFP fusion protein expression in companion cells (green fluorescence). Additional regulatory pathways include vernalization (through FLC repression), gibberellin signaling, and autonomous pathways, all converging to control flowering time.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.17": (
    caption: [Vernalization induces flowering in winter-annual types of Arabidopsis thaliana. The plant on the left is a winter-annual type that has not been exposed to cold and remains in a vegetative rosette state without flowering. The plant on the right is a genetically identical winter-annual type that was exposed to 40 days of temperatures slightly above freezing (vernalization treatment). The vernalized plant has transitioned to flowering, producing an inflorescence with flowers. This demonstrates the requirement for prolonged cold exposure to trigger flowering in winter annuals.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.18": (
    caption: [Duration of exposure to low temperature increases the stability of the vernalization effect. The longer that winter rye (*Secale cereale*) is exposed to a cold treatment, the greater the number of plants that remain vernalized when the cold treatment is followed by a devernalizing treatment of high temperature. The graph shows that short cold exposures (1-2 weeks) result in unstable vernalization that can be reversed, while longer exposures (6+ weeks) produce stable, irreversible vernalization. This demonstrates that vernalization involves a progressive change in gene expression stability.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.19": (
    caption: [Plants with a vernalization requirement are either quite delayed in flowering or do not flower unless they experience prolonged cold. (Left) Vernalization blocks the expression of the gene FLOWERING LOCUS C (FLC) in cold-requiring winter-annual ecotypes of Arabidopsis. FLC encodes a MADS-box transcription factor that represses flowering genes. (Right) A winter-annual plant shows dramatically delayed flowering compared to a vernalized plant or a rapid-cycling summer-annual ecotype that lacks the vernalization requirement. The molecular mechanism involves stable epigenetic silencing of FLC through histone modifications during cold exposure.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.20": (
    caption: [Inflorescence architecture in Arabidopsis. (A) The shoot apical meristem generates different organs at different developmental stages. Early in development, the shoot apical meristem forms a rosette of basal leaves. When the plant makes the transition to flowering, the shoot apical meristem is converted to an inflorescence meristem that produces cauline leaves and lateral floral meristems. Each floral meristem produces a complete flower. (B) Scanning electron micrographs showing the sequential development of the inflorescence meristem and emergence of floral meristems on its flanks.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.21": (
    caption: [Longitudinal sections through a vegetative (A) and a reproductive (B) shoot apical region of Arabidopsis. The vegetative meristem (A) is smaller and produces leaf primordia on its flanks. The reproductive inflorescence meristem (B) is larger and more dome-shaped, producing floral meristems on its flanks. The transition from vegetative to reproductive development involves changes in meristem size, shape, and the identity of lateral organs produced.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.22": (
    caption: [Floral organs are initiated sequentially by the floral meristem of Arabidopsis. (A and B) Scanning electron micrographs showing that floral organs are produced as successive whorls (concentric circles), starting with sepals on the outside and progressing inward through petals, stamens, and carpels. The floral meristem produces organs in a characteristic spiral or whorled pattern. (C) The temporal and spatial sequence of organ initiation demonstrates the highly organized developmental program controlling flower formation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.23": (
    caption: [Mutations in the floral organ identity genes dramatically alter flower structure. (A) Wild-type Arabidopsis shows normal structure with sepals, petals, stamens, and carpels in four concentric whorls. (B) *apetala2-2* mutants lack sepals and petals, with carpels in whorl 1 and stamens in whorls 2 and 3. (C) *pistillata2* mutants lack petals and stamens, with sepals in whorls 1 and 2 and carpels in whorls 3 and 4. (D) *agamous1* mutants lack both stamens and carpels, producing sepals and petals that repeat indefinitely in inner whorls. These homeotic transformations reveal the functions of organ identity genes.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.24": (
    caption: [A quadruple mutant of Arabidopsis (*ap1, ap2, ap3/pi, ag*) produces leaflike structures in place of floral organs. This demonstrates that when all floral organ identity genes are removed, the default developmental program produces leaf-like structures. The flowers lack normal whorl organization and phyllotaxy, instead producing organs that resemble vegetative leaves. This shows that floral organ identity genes are essential for specifying floral organ fate.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.25": (
    caption: [Interpretation of the phenotypes of floral homeotic mutants based on the ABC model. (A) In wild type, all three activity classes (A, B, and C) are functional and combine in specific whorls: A alone in whorl 1 (sepals), A+B in whorl 2 (petals), B+C in whorl 3 (stamens), and C alone in whorl 4 (carpels). (B) Loss of Class C activity results in expansion of Class A activity throughout the floral meristem, producing sepals-petals-petals-sepals. (C) Loss of Class A activity results in expansion of Class C activity, producing carpels-stamens-stamens-carpels. (D) Loss of Class B activity produces sepals-sepals-carpels-carpels. This demonstrates how combinatorial gene activity specifies organ identity.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.26": (
    caption: [ABCE model for floral development. (A) In *sepallata1-4* quadruple mutants, all floral organs resemble vegetative leaves, suggesting that SEP genes (Class E) are required for floral meristem identity and organ specification. (B) The ABCE model shows that SEP proteins are required in all four whorls for proper organ development. Class E genes work in combination with Class A genes for sepals (whorl 1), with A+B for petals (whorl 2), with B+C for stamens (whorl 3), and with C alone for carpels (whorl 4). The E genes are essential cofactors for ABC gene function.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.27": (
    caption: [Conversion of cotyledons and vegetative leaves into petals by ectopic expression of Class E genes in combination with Class A and B genes. Arabidopsis plants overexpressing SEP3/AP1/AP3/PI (A) or AP1/AP3/PI/SEP2/SEP3 (B) transgenes show dramatic homeotic transformations where normally vegetative organs develop petal characteristics including petal shape, color, and texture. This demonstrates that the combination of A, B, and E class genes is sufficient to confer petal identity even in non-floral organs, supporting the sufficiency of the ABCE model.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.28": (
    caption: [Model of MADS box domain interaction with target genes. (A) Domain structure of MADS box transcription factors showing the MADS domain (DNA binding), I region (protein-protein interaction), K domain (keratin-like coiled-coil for dimerization), and C-terminal region (transcriptional activation or repression). (B) Tetramers of MADS box transcription factors bind to pairs of CArG-box motifs (consensus sequence CC[A/T]6GG) in the regulatory regions of their target genes. The binding causes DNA bending, which may either activate or repress transcription depending on the specific proteins involved and regulatory context.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.29": (
    caption: [Quartet Model of floral organ specification in Arabidopsis. In whorl 1, expression of Class A (AP1 and AP2) and E (SEP) genes results in formation of sepals through A-E tetramers. In whorl 2, expression of Class A (AP1, AP2), B (AP3, PI), and E (SEP) genes results in petal formation through A-B-E tetramers. In whorl 3, expression of Class B (AP3, PI), C (AG), and E (SEP) genes results in stamen formation through B-C-E tetramers. In whorl 4, expression of Class C (AG) and E (SEP) genes results in carpel formation through C-E tetramers. This model proposes that organ identity is determined by specific quartets of MADS box proteins that form tetrameric transcriptional regulatory complexes.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.30": (
    caption: [Floral asymmetry in Antirrhinum (snapdragon). (A and B) Antirrhinum flowers exhibit bilateral symmetry (zygomorphy) with distinct dorsal (adaxial) and ventral (abaxial) sides. (C) The DIVARICATA (DIV) gene encodes a MYB transcription factor that promotes abaxial identity throughout the flower. CYCLOIDEA (CYC) and DICHOTOMA (DICH) encode related TCP transcription factors that promote dorsal identity. The interaction between these genes establishes the dorsoventral axis and bilateral symmetry, contrasting with the radial symmetry of many other flowers.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20.31": (
    caption: [The peloria mutant of toadflax (*Linaria vulgaris*). The normal flower of Linaria with bilateral symmetry is shown on the left, displaying the typical snapdragon-family zygomorphic structure. The radially symmetrical peloria mutant is shown on the right, exhibiting actinomorphic (radially symmetrical) flowers with five similar petals arranged in a star pattern. The peloric toadflax flower is caused by inactivation of the Linaria CYCLOIDEA gene through epigenetic DNA methylation rather than DNA sequence mutation. This represents an epimutation affecting floral symmetry, demonstrating that epigenetic changes can produce heritable phenotypic variation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  )
)
